ia|Saudi Arabia]]\n* {{flagof|India|name=''Tiranga''}} (\"The Tricolour\"), India\n* {{flagof|Iceland|variant=naval|name=''Tj\u00faguf\u00e1ni''}}, state flag of Iceland\n* {{flagof|Thailand|name=''Trairong''}} (\"Tricolour\"), Thailand\n* {{flagof|Isle of Man|name=''Tree Cassyn Vannin''}} (\"Three Legs of Mann\"), Isle of Man\n* ''Tricolor'' or similar, a term for several national flags which are [[Triband (flag)|triband]]s or [[Tricolour (flag)|tricolour]]s:\n** {{flagof|Bolivia|name=''La Tricolor''}} (\"The Tricolor\"), Bolivia\n** {{flagof|Colombia|name=''El Tricolor Nacional''}} (\"The National Tricolor\"), Colombia\n** {{flagof|Costa Rica|name=''La Tricolor''}}, Costa Rica\n** {{flagof|Croatia|name=''Trobojnica''}} (\"The Tricolor\"), Croatia\n** {{flagof|Ecuador|name=''La Tricolor''}}, Ecuador\n** {{flagof|Venezuela|name=''Tricolor Nacional''}} (\"National Tricolour\"), Venezuela\n** {{flagof|Spain|variant=1931|link=Flag of the Second Spanish Republic|name=''La Tricolor''}}, Second Spanish Republic (historical)\n** {{flagof|France|name=''Drapeau Tricolore''}} (\"Tricolour Flag\"), France\n** {{flagof|Italy|name=''Il Tricolore''}}, Italy\n** {{flagof|Romania|name=''Tricolorul''}}, Romania\n** {{flagof|Russia|name=''\u0422\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0440''}} (''Trikolor''), Russia\n* {{flagof|Ireland|name=''Tr\u00eddhathach na h\u00c9ireann''}} (\"Irish tricolour\"), Ireland\n* {{flagof|Sicily|name=''Trinacria''}}, Sicily\n* {{flagof|Lithuania|name=''Trispalv\u0117''}}, Lithuania\n\n==U==\n* {{flagof|Azerbaijan|name=''\u00dc\u00e7r\u0259ngli Bayraq''}} (\"Tricolour Flag\"), Azerbaijan\n* {{flagof|Haiti|link=}} ''L'Union Fait La Force'' (\"[[Unity makes strength]]\"), motto on the [[flag of Haiti]]\n* {{flagof|United Kingdom|link=Union Jack|name=''Union Jack''}} or ''Union Flag'',{{efn|Called the \"Royal Union Flag\" in Canada, a former colony of the United Kingdom and current Dominion.}} [[Flag of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]\n* {{flagof|United States|link=Jack of the United States|image=US Naval Jack.svg|name=''Union Jack''}}, United States\n\n==W==\n* {{flagof|image=Banner of the Qulla Suyu.svg}} ''[[Wiphala]]'', a flag representing the native peoples of the Andes and the co-official [[flag of Bolivia]]\n*  {{flagof|China|name=\u4e94\u661f\u7ea2\u65d7}} (''W\u01d4 X\u012bng H\u00f3ng Q\u00ed'') (\"Five-Starred Red Flag\"), People's Republic of China\n\n==Y==\n* {{flagof|Wales|name=''Y Ddraig Goch''}} (\"The Red Dragon\"), Wales\n* {{flagof|Confederate States of America|1863|name=''The White Man's Flag''}}, Confederate States\n* {{flagof|Armenia|name=''\u0535\u057c\u0561\u0563\u0578\u0582\u0575\u0576''}} (''Yerakooyn'') (\"Tricolour\"), Armenia\n\n==Z==\n* {{flagof|Ukraine|name=''\u0436\u043e\u0432\u0442\u043e-\u0431\u043b\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439 (\u043f\u0440\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0440)''}} (''Zhovto-blakytnyy [prapor]'') (\"Yellow-blue [flag]\"), Ukraine\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists and galleries of flags| Names]]\n[[Category:Lists of names|flag names]]\n", "name_user": "31.215.242.71", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_flag_names"}
{"title_page": "Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)", "text_new": "{{for|the 2000 series|Randall & Hopkirk (Deceased) (2000 TV series)}}\n{{short description|British television series (1969\u20131970)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{infobox television\n| show_name = Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)\n| italic_title= no\n| image = Randall and Hopkirk Deceased titlecard.jpg\n| alt = Series title over a hand\n| caption =\n| show_name_2          = My Partner the Ghost\n| genre                = [[Occult detective fiction]]<br>Supernatural horror fiction<br>[[Crime thriller]]\n| creator              = [[Dennis Spooner]]\n| developer            =\n| writer               =\n| director             =\n| creative_director    =\n| presenter            =\n| starring             = [[Mike Pratt (actor)|Mike Pratt]]<br />[[Kenneth Cope]]<br />[[Annette Andre]]\n| judges               =\n| voices               =\n| narrated             =\n| theme_music_composer = [[Edwin Astley]]\n| opentheme            =\n| endtheme             =\n| composer             = Edwin Astley\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_series           = 1\n| num_episodes         = 26\n| list_episodes        = #Episode list\n| executive_producer   =\n| producer             = [[Monty Berman]]\n| editor               =\n| location             =\n| cinematography       =\n| camera               =\n| runtime              = 49 minutes\n| company              = Scoton<br>[[ITC Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[ITV Studios Global Entertainment|Carlton Communications plc]]\n| channel              = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| picture_format       = [[35mm movie film|35mm film]] [[Aspect ratio (image)|4:3]] Colour\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_run            =\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1969|9|19|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|1970|3|13|df=y}}\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| related              =\n| website              =\n| website_title        =\n| production_website   =\n}}\n'''''Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)'''''  is a British [[private detective]] [[television series]], starring [[Mike Pratt (actor)|Mike Pratt]] and [[Kenneth Cope]] respectively as the private detectives Jeff Randall and [[Marty Hopkirk]]. The series was created by [[Dennis Spooner]] and produced by [[Monty Berman]], and was first broadcast in 1969 and 1970. In the United States, it was given the title '''''My Partner the Ghost'''''. \n[[ITC Entertainment]] produced a single series of 26 episodes in 1968 and 1969, which was aired from September 1969 to March 1970. The [[pilot episode]] was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in the United Kingdom on 19 September 1969 on [[ATV Midlands]]. [[LWT]] broadcast the pilot on 21 September 1969.\n\nThe series was [[Randall & Hopkirk (Deceased) (2000 TV series)|remade in 2000]], starring British [[comedy]] duo [[Vic & Bob|Vic Reeves and Bob Mortimer]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn the initial episode, Hopkirk is murdered during an investigation but returns as a [[ghost]]. Randall is the only main character able to see or hear him, although certain minor characters are also able to do so in various circumstances throughout the series, such as mediums, or drunk, or under hypnosis.\n==Production==\n===Conception===\nThe idea for the series was conceived by Dennis Spooner who had an adjoining office to producer Monty Berman at Elstree Studios. They had already collaborated on ''[[The Champions]]''. In March 1968 the pair conceived ''[[Department S (TV series)|Department S]]'' and Spooner's interest in the paranormal inspired by several feature films contemplated the possibility of a television series featuring a ghost and that a detective series would offer greater scope for storylines.\nThe idea was put to Head of ATV [[Lew Grade]] but he was not enthusiastic as the series lacked a leading American which he felt would inhibit overseas sales. Fortunately the synopsis caught the eye of [[Ralph Smart]] who had worked on ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'', ''[[The Invisible Man (1958 TV series)|The Invisible Man]]'', and ''[[Danger Man]]'' and he wanted to write the pilot. This convinced Lew Grade to green light the series.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tibbles |first1=Geoff |title=Randall & Hopkirk deceased |publisher=Boxtree |isbn=9780752209159 |pages=11 & 12}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nJeff Randall, originally named Steven Randall, was considered for the comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]] who had made ''Tonight with Dave Allen'' for Lew Grade's ATV. When Allen signed for the [[BBC]] attention turned to Mike Pratt who had appeared in a number of episodes of various [[ITC Entertainment|ITC]] series and was deemed to be right for the part by the production team including [[Cyril Frankel]], creative consultant on the series.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Programme notes Randall & Hopkirk |journal=DVD booklet |pages=6}}</ref>\n\nMarty Hopkirk proved more difficult and some actors were considered after scouring the pages of casting resource [[Spotlight (company)|Spotlight]], Frankel was at a new Italian restaurant in [[Soho, London]] and sitting at the next table was Kenneth Cope, with his wife, and Frankel though he would be right for the part. Frankel told Monty Berman, directed a screen test and Cope got the part.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Programme notes Randall & Hopkirk |journal=DVD booklet |pages=7}}</ref>\n\nJean Hopkirk, not in the original concept, is portrayed by Australian actress Annette Andr\u00e9. She was well known to the production team, having appeared in six episodes of ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' as well as ''[[The Baron]]''. She had been short listed for one of the lead roles in ''The Champions'' but lost to [[Alexandra Bastedo]], reportedly at the whim of an American [[CBS]] executive.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tibbles |first1=Geoff |title=Randall and Hopkirk deceased |publisher=Boxtree |isbn=9780752209159 |pages=20}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and locations===\nFilming commenced with the pilot in May 1968 with the aim to shoot a 48-minute episode over a fortnight working Monday to Friday from 8:30am to 5:30pm with some filming on alternate Sundays. The bulk of filming with the main cast was on two sound stages at ABC Elstree in Borehamwood where ''Department S'' and other series were also in production. Establishing shots would use library footage. Location sequences were usually filmed by a second unit using stand-ins or the guest cast who were only needed for one episode filmed by one director while the main cast were completing the previous episode with another director.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Programme notes Randall & Hopkirk Booklet |publisher=network |pages=9}}</ref> To keep costs down, a simple [[jump cut]] was used to make Marty Hopkirk disappear and reappear. Walking through walls was costly and time consuming using an image reflected on plain glass at an angle in front of the camera  often used in the theatre called [[Pepper's ghost]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tibballs |first1=geoff |title=Randall & Hopkirk |publisher=Boxtree |isbn=9780752209159 |pages=24}}</ref>\n\nThe exterior of the Randall & Hopkirk's office was a doorway at the side of Adam's Furniture Fabric on the corner of Kymberly Road and Springfield Road in Harrow now completely redeveloped as St George's Shopping Centre. Jeff Randall's flat was located at Hanover House close to the corner of St John's Wood High Street and Jean Hopkirk's flat was on Lauderdale Road, Maida Vale, London.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Randall & Hopkirk programme notes |publisher=Network DVD |pages=12 & 25}}</ref>\n\nNumerous country houses in the northern Greater London and Hertfordshire area were used for the external shots of the many mansions featured in the series. In the  \"[[For the Girl Who Has Everything (Randall and Hopkirk Deceased)|For the Girl Who Has Everything]]\" episode the exterior of [[Hilfield Castle]] in [[Aldenham]] was used for Kim Wentworth's ([[Lois Maxwell]]'s) home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randallandhopkirk.org.uk/locations_03_for_the_girl_who_has_everything.htm|title=Locations:For the Girl Who Has Everything|publisher=Randallandhopkirk.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The Tudor-looking Edgwarebury Hotel on Barnet Lane in Elstree, now The Manor Elstree, was used in the episodes \"[[Who Killed Cock Robin? (Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased))|Who Killed Cock Robin?]]\" and \"[[The House on Haunted Hill]]\" episodes and a plethora of other ITC series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randallandhopkirk.org.uk/locations_06_who_killed_cock_robin.htm\n|title=Locations:Who Killed Cock Robin?|publisher=Randallandhopkirk.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The exterior of the Lambert Clinic in the comical episode \"[[A Disturbing Case]]\", written by Mike Pratt himself, is now the Institute of Grocery Distribution in [[Letchmore Heath]], Hertfordshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randallandhopkirk.org.uk/locations_22_disturbing_case.htm\n|title=Locations:A Disturbing Case|publisher=Randallandhopkirk.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The Seaton Residence, a large white house with Doric columns at the front used in \"[[The Smile Behind the Veil]]\" episode is the Dyrham Park Country Club, the club house of a golf club in Galley Lane, [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randallandhopkirk.org.uk/locations_07_the_smile_behind_the_veil.htm|title=Locations:The Smile Behind the Veil|publisher=Randallandhopkirk.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dyrhampark.com/|title=Welcome to Dyrham Park Country Club|publisher=dyrhampark.com|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> [[Woburn Abbey]] in [[Woburn, Bedfordshire]], is featured in the episode \"[[The Man from Nowhere (Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased))|The Man from Nowhere]]\" and is visited by Jeannie and a Marty imposter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randallandhopkirk.org.uk/locations_16_man_from_nowhere.htm|title=Locations:The Man from Nowhere|publisher=Randallandhopkirk.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cars===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Vauxhall Victor white.jpg\n| width1 = 180\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = 1960s red mini.jpg\n| width2 = 180\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Left:White Vauxhall Victor. Right:Red Mini\n}}\nThe car Jeff Randall drove was a white [[Vauxhall Victor]] registration RXD996F which was also used in two episodes of ''Department S''; in that series [[Joel Fabiani]]'s character Stewart Sullivan drove a white Vauxhall with the registration RXD997F. The red Mini used by Jean Hopkirk was registered in May 1964 and had been used in an episode of ''The Saint'' (1968), an episode of ''Department S'' (1969) and driven by [[Tony Curtis]]'s character Danny Wilde in an episode of ''[[The Persuaders!]]'' (1970).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Randall & Hopkirk programme notes |publisher=Network DVD |pages=12}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe theme music was composed by [[Edwin Astley]] who in the previous years had composed many themes and incidental music for film series produced and distributed by [[ITC Entertainment|ITC]] and its forerunners. Astley used the harpsicord because of its distinctive sound and used the C minor key because of the \"death\" part in it. In all Astley composed 188 numbered cues used throughout the series. Music composed by Astley from  ''The Champions'' was briefly used as was music by [[Albert Elms]] from the same series. Music was also used by Astley from his own library of music, the [[Chappell & Co.|Chappell]] library, and other music composed by [[Robert Farnon]], [[Johnny Hawksworth]], [[Sidney Torch]], [[Antonio Vivaldi|Vivaldi]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tibballs |first1=geoff |title=Randall & Hopkirk deceased |publisher=Boxtree |isbn=9780752209159 |pages=30\u201331}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Pixley |first1=Andrew |title=Randall & Hopkirk deceased 3CD original soundtrack booklet |publisher=Network |pages=4, 21, 22, 23}}</ref>\n\n==Characters and cast==\n[[File:Mikeprattjeffrandall.jpg|thumb|right|Jeff Randall]]\n* '''[[Mike Pratt (actor)|Mike Pratt]]''' as '''Jeff Randall''' - a successful, albeit a \"slightly seedy\"<ref name=\"Goldman2013\">{{cite book|last=Goldman|first=Lawrence|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography 2005-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nbGcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA90|date=7 March 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967154-0|page=90}}</ref> and often morally ambiguous private detective whose success in solving mysteries becomes inevitably greater once he has the benefits and [[paranormal]] abilities of his deceased friend and partner Marty Hopkirk. Randall is short-tempered, becoming particularly irritated with certain situations and people, particularly the ghost of Marty.\n* '''[[Kenneth Cope]]''' as '''Marty Hopkirk''' -  a private detective and Jeff's partner who is murdered in the line of duty after being run down by a [[automobile|car]] travelling at high speed. Hopkirk dies instantly, but returns to help Jeff (the only living person who can see him) bring his killer to justice. Marty remains with Jeff throughout the entire series, a cynical, often perturbed character who torments Jeff as much as helps him. \n* '''[[Annette Andre]]''' as '''Jeannie Hopkirk''' - the young widow of Marty who works as a secretary at the Randall and Hopkirk private investigation office. Though attractive and resourceful, she can be very naive and vulnerable, putting her own life in danger on many occasions.\n* [[Ivor Dean]] as Inspector Large (5 episodes) - a lugubrious police inspector, always suspicious of Randall and looking to arrest him. Their relationship is highly adversarial, though Randall eventually helps the inspector bring the real culprits to justice.\n* [[Richard Kerley]] as Sergeant Hinds (3 episodes) - Inspector Large's subordinate. \n* [[Judith Arthy]]  as Jennifer (2 episodes) - Jennifer is the sister of Jeannie, who comes to London to visit her sister.\n* [[Garfield Morgan]] as Carlson (2 episodes)\n* [[Michael Griffiths (actor)|Michael Griffiths]] as Inspector Nelson (2 episodes) - a police inspector, who much like Inspector Dean, treats Randall as a criminal and the first suspect for various crimes.\n\n{{hidden begin|border=solid #aaa 1px|title=Other actors appearing in the series:}}\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n'''A'''\n* [[Raymond Adamson]]\n* [[Neal Arden]]\n* [[Graham Armitage]]\n* [[John Arnatt]]\n* [[Robin Askwith]]\n* [[Roger Avon]]\n* [[Felix Aylmer]]\n\n'''B'''\n* [[Anthony Baird]]\n* [[Simon Barnes (actor)|Simon Barnes]]\n* [[Patrick Barr]]\n* [[Keith Barron]]\n* [[Alexandra Bastedo]]\n* [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]]\n* [[Norman Beaton]]\n* [[Bruce Beeby]]\n* [[Michael Beint]]\n* [[James Belchamber]]\n* [[Francis Bennett (actor)|Francis Bennett]]\n* [[Dick Bentley]]\n* [[Harold Berens]]\n* [[Paul Bertoya]]\n* [[Michael Bird (actor)|Michael Bird]]\n* [[Norman Bird]]\n* [[Caroline Blakiston]]\n* [[Joby Blanshard]]\n* [[Brian Blessed]]\n* [[John Bott (actor)|John Bott]]\n* [[Tom Bowman (actor)|Tom Bowman]]\n* [[John Boxer (British actor)|John Boxer]]\n* [[Penny Brahms]]\n* [[Edward Brayshaw]]\n* [[James Bree (actor)|James Bree]]\n* [[Susan Broderick]]\n* [[Ray Brooks (actor)|Ray Brooks]]\n* [[Arthur Brough]]\n* [[A.J. Brown]]\n* [[Gabrielle Brune]]\n* [[John Bryans]]\n* [[Denise Buckley]]\n* [[Keith Buckley (actor)|Keith Buckley]]\n* [[Alfred Burke]]\n* [[Jeremy Burnham]]\n* [[Ian Butler (actor)|Ian Butler]]\n'''C'''\n*[[Edward Caddick]]\n*[[Richard Caldicot]]\n*[[Joyce Carey]]\n*[[David Cargill (actor)|David Cargill]]\n*[[Veronica Carlson]]\n*[[Martin Carrol]]\n*[[Dave Carter (actor)|Dave Carter]]\n*[[Ann Castle]]\n*[[John Cazabon]]\n*[[Clive Cazes]]\n*[[Peter Cellier]]\n*[[Nicolas Chagrin]]\n*[[Tricia Chapman]]\n*[[Tom Chatto]]\n*[[Basil Clarke (actor)|Basil Clarke]]\n*[[Carol Cleveland]]\n*[[Linda Cole]]\n*[[Michael Coles (actor)|Michael Coles]]\n*[[John Collin (actor)|John Collin]]\n*[[Patrick Conner]]\n*[[George A. Cooper]]\n*[[Billy Cornelius (actor)|Billy Cornelius]]\n*[[Adrienne Corri]]\n*[[Nicholas Courtney]]\n*[[Clifford Cox]]\n*[[Tracey Crisp]]\n*[[Roger Croucher]]\n*[[James Culliford]]\n*[[Roland Curran]]\n\n'''D'''\n*[[Henry Davies (actor)|Henry Davies]]\n*[[Noel Davis]]\n*[[Anne De Vigier]]\n*[[Hans De Vries]]\n*[[Roger Delgado]]\n*[[Roy Desmond]]\n*[[Arnold Diamond]]\n*[[Basil Dignam]]\n*[[Carol Dilworth]]\n*[[Eric Dodson]]\n*[[James Donnelly (British actor)|James Donnelly]]\n*[[Rosemary Donnelly]]\n*[[David Downer]]\n*[[Terry Duggan]]\n*[[William Dysart]]\n'''E'''\n*[[Clifford Earl]]\n*[[Meredith Edwards (actor)|Meredith Edwards]]\n*[[Christopher Eedy]]\n*[[Peter Jay Elliott]]\n*[[Eva Enger]]\n*[[Norman Eshley]]\n*[[Clifford Evans (actor)|Clifford Evans]]\n*[[Tenniel Evans]]\n'''F'''\n*[[Max Faulkner (actor)|Max Faulkner]]\n*[[Gerald Flood]]\n*[[David Forbes (actor)|David Forbes]]\n*[[Michael Forrest]]\n*[[Dudley Foster]]\n*[[Grazina Frame]]\n*[[John Fraser (actor)|John Fraser]]\n*[[Liz Fraser]]\n'''G'''\n*[[Chris Gannon (actor)|Chris Gannon]]\n*[[John Garvin (actor)|John Garvin]]\n*[[Sue Gerrard]]\n*[[Alan Gifford]]\n*[[Michael Goldie]]\n*[[Michael Goodliffe]]\n*[[Howard Goorney]]\n*[[Romo Gorrara]]\n*[[Michael Gothard]]\n*[[Michael Gover]]\n*[[Michael Graham (actor)|Michael Graham]]\n*[[Danny Green (actor)|Danny Green]]\n*[[Earl Green]]\n*[[Keith Grenville]]\n*[[Michael Gwynn]]\n'''H'''\n*[[Patricia Haines]]\n*[[John Hallam]]\n*[[Olivia Hamnett]]\n*[[Doris Hare]]\n*[[Juliet Harmer]]\n*[[John Harvey (actor)|John Harvey]]\n*[[Robin Hawdon]]\n*[[David Healy (actor)|David Healy]]\n*[[Thomas Heathcote]]\n*[[Maurice 